The Prague Stock Exchange fell to the minuse at the end of trading
After a sharp slump in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange has continued its slump since the beginning of Tuesday's trading session, falling by nearly six percent.
This time, the decline is due to a slump in Wall Street stock.
In our country, too, the market’s response to the outcome of the vote of the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan for stabilizing the financial sector.
The Fall of Equities in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday was experienced by stocks on stock exchanges in Asia, although indices eventually erased some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng index wrote off nearly four percent during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, in Shanghai, the markets were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five per cent but eventually cut losses to 4.3 per cent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell 3.6 percent, according to the index.
"The timing of the rescue operation in the U.S. is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary policy office.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy independently, without depending on China’s central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates at the same level as the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should urgently return to negotiations and approve the proposal to support the financial system, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd.
Otherwise, other countries are at risk of feeling the impact.
Blood bath of U.S. stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected a plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 trillion CZK) were to be spent.
Lawmakers have thus ignored President George W. Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indexes recorded the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, and the slump in the similar range was last recorded in 1987.
The index was already falling before the vote, but as soon as it became clear that the bill had not passed in the House, the index found itself in free fall.
Congress backs down: U.S. government can pump $700bn into banks
Top U.S. Congressional leaders and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of a financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
There will be a vote on it early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks on approving a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance for the U.S. financial system of 700 billion dollars (around 12 trillion crowns).
However, it has not yet been won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final form of the law.
The financial system's support plan will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to sources, the plan could be voted on probably not before Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that a rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
However, there will then be a "sobering up" thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the form of the market stabilization package should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
The final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers' representatives met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson last night to give a definitive form to the government's fund.
It should buy back from financial companies unsaleable mortgage assets that drag financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the brink of a definitive agreement of a plan that will work and be effective in the market as well.
We still need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where congressional decisions could affect Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear with certainty when the two chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether they can be stuck to a last-minute hearing on a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be approved in the next few days.
But the law will still undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial 350 billion dollars is to be available as soon as possible, as President George W. Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in the sequence of another 100 billion dollars and later the final 350 billion dollars.
Bush praises progress in negotiations
The president may veto this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of a program that was to raise funds to buy back bad mortgage securities, the value of which has plummeted because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has remained.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Sen. Judd Gregg said in a statement.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress in negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restrictions on golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, a senior negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, making concessions, timing funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of corporate participants in the program and establishes a committee to have oversight over the fund.
It should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said in a statement.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who have trouble repaying.
The government should negotiate new repayments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of repayments for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to David Mark, chief economist at Patria Finance, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And that's because it's not known what mechanism and at what cost the troubled assets will be redeemed.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will share their losses," Marek told news server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or early next week is not so important, according to Mark.
“It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they support the plan and that they will sanctify it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on approval is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, combined, has 29 percent
The significant weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition and the significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties have brought, according to the first preliminary results, Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, where the position of the current chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously shaking.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Corutan Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the strongest party in the country remains the social democracy (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the vote, but loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the last election in 2006.
The ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent, was even worse.
These are the worst results of both of these big parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially for the people who triggered the early elections, literally a disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the people's people had a significant lead over the SPÖ in their preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government crash.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an emergency meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the increasingly likely exit from the election result, i.e. the restoration of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, due to the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) gained preliminary 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed fears of a repeat of 1999, when the people agreed with populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 split from BZÖ) to a joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider is clearly betting on these developments, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with either party and foresees a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Green Party also made it to parliament, but it lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties apparently crossed the four percent threshold and did not make it to parliament.
