The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
He might not miss long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
After all, this was confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are held so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, after all, we have three mobile networks and penetration high over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (CTU), Pavel Dvořák, has often said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with its own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, which were then also to be responded to by classic operators.
Even before the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for example.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, the operator managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they need much fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaply as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a fresh target group can also be a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys are choosing Mobilking - an operator they like and who they can trust," says David Seibertz CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, running this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be caught in our country.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone’s spokesperson, doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been the GTS Novera group for a long time, so it would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already managed to advance the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's press secretary.
Maybe it's flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be waiting maybe by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific than other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónika O2 press department said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also appealing to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, adds in rare agreement with O2: "We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
He adds: "It's hard to have a virtual operator on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to consider in this short term.”
Vodafone is focusing its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepicický says: "By dealing with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decline in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators are interested in something, they can pull together, also testifies to the tug-of-war around the formation of U:fon.
Probably the greatest pressure towards CTU went at the time of the creation of U:fon from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from the CTU website.
But now it is U:fon that is suitable as an argument for not admitting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently enhanced by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of Czech regulators is striking.
It is not just the attitude of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
However, he took his typical attitude towards the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract was concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classic operators," Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office said in response to our question.
It will probably not surprise the representatives of the operators of the statement.
From an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, make sure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than considered.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is not among the interests of the Office.
In fact, shocking about the whole case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators that result from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is entirely offered by itself.
Like the exact same price of petrol at gas stations, it is certainly only a work of chance and a tough competitive struggle.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore it does not have adequately responsible for its conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably missing even for the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
Interpreting the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the CTU, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning for the Office that three mobile operators proceed strikingly similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The murmuning of responsibility at CTU is then a relatively usual trick in telecommunications, which the Office puts its hands away from the whole matter.
We have already encountered him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not push for the extension of the CTU’s powers to competition in telecommunications, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
This must be known more than well by the representatives of the Office, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It goes when no one is watching
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, which are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
Its own mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová said in response to our question about the issue.
However, it is unlikely that such activity will be brought to the responsible people of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators oppose such a procedure.
They have considerable profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, do not endanger them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot have it fully with it as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This should be at least strange for CTU.
In addition, another question for the Office opens up.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to settle for the explanation of the operators that they have no idea about such a thing and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When won't we be the most expensive
As has already been done several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and another was packed on it.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are tossing the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot shake the impression that the lack of competence suits them more than in these cases.
But let's not throw the flint into the rye.
If behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really soon appear in our country, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the Office to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more expensively than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four versions of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented new recordings of the national anthem Where My Home on the occasion of the Czech Statehood Day.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choral submission and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka performed singing.
The authors of the hymn modifications are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the server iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymens.
He previously told Czech Radio that he deliberately selected singers with young representative voices for singing solo variants, which are distinctive and popular.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that they had a clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they would agree," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where My Home was first performed in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
She gained popularity and people spontaneously took her as their own.
The first stanza of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven state symbols remained even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
