Prague public transport on Wednesday will also ride a chip for the first time
Wednesday 1. October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will board the metro, trams and buses.
At this time, it can buy about a hundred thousand people who own an Opencard smart card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their chip card uploaded to their smart card in the information centers and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred customers took advantage of the service by the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the dispensing windows in the metro stations, where they have until now had to stand regularly in long queues for paper tickets.
They buy the coupon over the Internet and upload it to the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"There is a counter with trained service available to passengers at these places, which will help those interested with the online purchase and also upload the purchased coupon to their card," said Martin Opatrný, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service machines, which are mounted in several metro lobbys.
What do slot machines look like?
They are red, resemble ticket markers and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. p. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five of them in the city, but there should be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný added.
The coupon will check the driver's seat automaton
The operation of the vending machines, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
