Even rats have feelings
When a rat or a cockroach flees danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Joseph LeDoux, a neurologist, is convinced that many animals have feelings.
But how would it be possible to verify whether they feel the same thing when they behave similarly to us?
Posts from well-known scientists have been published in the online journal "Edge" for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without being able to prove it, or anyone else, when we cannot prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we start to focus on a different kind and open up questions of perception or universal consciousness, we enter into impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets into danger, it will do the same thing that many other animals do: it will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
People behave similarly, of which some scientists conclude on a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal experience.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This extensive region is significantly more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to assume that one is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the linguistic nature of a person: because such a large part of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to the language, it would certainly influence the language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed it may be, would probably differ from most states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, it puts us in great trouble to explore it.
Most of my inferences relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition, there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more easily accessible.
It would be possible to examine the processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was addressed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on the neural correlats of consciousness rather than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I infer them from the fact that an emotional system like a system of fear is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is thus the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as body reactions) uses the operating memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely intertwined with those areas of the cortex that characterize primates, and especially people.
In connection with linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradification of perception, because by means of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states to attribute them side by side to others.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to body sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could easily participate in the feelings perceived by multiple animal genera.
In theory, I cannot contradict it, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear to us in rats and humans is probably felt by both organisms in the same way: But how is it possible to verify, Pankseep further says whether rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the conformity of experiencing.
It is true that the neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain stems, on the other hand, cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for the feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in a man: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who know?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how I should prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I examine emotional behavior rather than the emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and in humans.
As with rats, I don't research my language and consciousness, I don't even experience feelings, I don't know if they exist.
It can be considered short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
