But today, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is being applied - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I got on a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was supposed to meet with one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kinikioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a crushing ride on the tracks that reminded me of the old-world rhythms of the well-known documentary Night Post, I arrived in a Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigms of Turkish consensus.
In the west, she raised suspicions, especially in Washington.
The taxi brought me to the main AKP tent, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, deliberately built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power-based handlings, where medium-sized managers in commercial suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning shops.
Suat Kinikioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its border.
Today, they have to look to the east and the west at the same time.
It was no choice.
It had to do both.
"But there will definitely come a time," I asked, "when will Turkey have to make a decision?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want such a decision to take place."
After that, he emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the surrounding Black Sea are as good for Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, drive on these tracks to the east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back to the Hydarpasha station, after another mostly sleepy night, I thought of the two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Con, who watched this building build a century ago.
