Here in New York, we all speak fluently financially
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If Manhattan tourists had stayed away from Newstacks and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't have realized they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the glass-filled beehive of offices over their heads, every day, bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst "bad day in the office" since the 1929 crisis.
The metsmen are still rumbling with metal carts on the sidewalks and are carrying muffin pans to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics are still moving between the towers and wearing, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from the scales on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the street menus, and it's still not possible to get a yellow cab between four and seven in the afternoon on a weekday.
It didn't look like a crisis at all, until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this task to cover with a late afternoon siesta at my local branch of JP Morgan Chase, there were already about twenty people waiting in the queue.
Not in front of the cash registers to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of the counter where older clients order cheque books, tourists ask about the way to the Macy's convenience store, and new customers set up bills.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason as I did.
However, compared to me, they have already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in the places where they arrived, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They have collected money from so-called thrifts (a bit similar to building societies), cash associations and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state, and which claim to care for their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have gone quietly bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a 327-billion-dollar asset bank, went into bankruptcy, and when New Yorkers were returning home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with assets worth $440 billion, tried to hunt down a bailout buyer.
Office and shop staff who stood in front of me and feared another collapse were moving their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and which makes most of the bailout on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned their financials fluently over the past week.
Some woman in my local Chinese supermarket was talking on the phone and speaking to Lehman Borthers, the bankrupt bank, and her skinny chief executive, Dick Fuld, with such familiality, as if she were scratching a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed roughly fifty-year-old housekeeper of my apartment building, has changed the subject of our ordinary conversation - Brad, Angelina or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me: "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I moved it, I won't take any chances.'
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's music leader since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, 9/11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and choir.
As part of the district music plan, he founded an excellent choir of young Proteus for a year.
He was supposed to be under the age of 21, but by the time Proteus sang last time in 1979, a few of us were almost 30 - we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (mythological shape changer) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to embark on any music that was presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with the entire orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often stunning, always exciting, and all thanks to the inspiration of that one man and enthusiasm for music that remained completely unchanging all the time.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself."
He said: "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
Then sing it! "
His baton technique was absolutely clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the musical standard was, he always lifted it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor was to be knighted, then it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well in the two decades when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
I've reviewed more than 100 of his concerts over the past 40 years and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed with any of them - and I've been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "pulled one or two soaked rocks around the world."
Many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary, William Woodruff (25 September), claims that "in 1946 he returned to economic history in Oxford and in 1950 became a researcher on Houblon-Norman...while studying at BSc, MA and PhD."
This is based on Woodruff's note from the author's in Beyond Nab End, but it's not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953, he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, and at that time completed a dissertation on the British rubber industry, which was led by Professor J. D. Chambers, and subsequently published it in 1958 as a publication of the British Rubber Industry.
He actually spent the years 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the University of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff has gone over this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from Austria's right-wing Free Party and Filip Dewinter of Belgium's right-wing Vlaams Belang party, is taking part in a demonstration that presented the "Cities Against Islamization" organization in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that display mosques crossed out of the red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend in which extreme right-wing parties made huge gains in general elections.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were severely damaged between Friday evening and this morning, and the police are convinced that it was an organized event.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols such as David's star on some graves, but detectives are convinced that it may have been an attempt to disguise the motives of extremists led by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident was in any way linked to the election.
A spokesman for the Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration that comes as the Muslim month of Ramadan nears the end.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering the wheel of finding its own soul after it swung to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which received more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, have waged a vehemently anti-immigrant campaign, and some of their slogans have been condemned by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Free Party, which won over 18 percent of the vote, protested against headscarves and burqas in the campaign, and even expressed his opposition to the food in which the relationship to Islam is perceived.
At his last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" designed to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that these are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the elections that put the extreme right in the position of the country's strongest political bloc suggest that this change was mainly due to young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed on a trip abroad
Gary Glitter, a glamrock star who was convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned by the court from travelling to France and Spain.
Officials have imposed this six-month ban on Glitter after informing monitoring authorities that he plans to travel through France to Spain.
The Kent police were granted a travel ban last Thursday after giving officials evidence of Glitter's past sentences for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford's lowest criminal court in Kent but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A judicial service spokesman said: "On Thursday, September 25, at Ashford's lowest criminal court, the Kent police asked for a regulation that would prevent Mr. Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until March 25.
Paul Gadd did not attend personally.”
The 64-year-old Glitter informed authorities that he wished to travel abroad, as required by his record in the register of sexual attackers.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They also have to hand over the scheduled departure date to the police a week in advance.
If the duty to inform the authorities omitted, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent police have announced that they will not discuss individual cases of Glitter's possible travels around the county.
A Kent police spokeswoman said: "The Kent police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it's easier to track someone who stays in Britain because we have vast systems that handle potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting Kent residents is a top priority for the Kent police, and we are working closely to monitor the behaviour of recorded sexual assailants to reduce any danger to the public to a minimum.”
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for the abuse of two girls, aged 10 and 11.
