On August 22, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and remained there while his attorney, David Corker, went to Uxbridge's lowest criminal court in west London, and at the same time Scotland Yard successfully requested an order that required him to register as a sex attacker.
Glitter was previously jailed in the UK for four months for owning child pornography.
An Interior Ministry source said Jacqui Smith, the interior minister, is calm and glad Glitter was prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off the scene." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no ruffles or costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus on interpretation - I will only achieve the relaxed expression of a man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other - man.
Inseparable, apart from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then one can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a glimpse of the captured gaze, or the passionate gesture of the hands, which are carefree, because they are not going to step on the scene.
The German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of performing with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which runs as part of the moon photography program flamenca (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), "reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco," the author says, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "may be any people, but when you look at the photos, you will find that these are not typical pictures of artists on the scene.
These people, portrayed "on the street", are artists capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that will allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portrait flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The application of different stylistic means contradicts the classical basis of the film and lends it to the contemporary spirit, which is an idea that, according to Bauer himself, is mirrored by flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, which, however, continues to surprise and evolve."
What pulls the audience is not the action of the dance itself, singing or play, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we encounter the most important, the spirit that appears in the way of perception, being and experiencing, it was and is a constant of the work presented during these days in the El Fotomata gallery.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known characters of flamenco, such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon be published in a book, which will contain exhibited portraits.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to the idea of repeating the idea of "Portraits of a Sports Veteran" ("SportARTproject") two years ago.
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people," the photographer admits that "photographing people, getting to know them and having the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or just short, to enter their lives - that's my passion.
I think in photography, the portrait is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or encounters people, personalities he sometimes doesn’t even know, or give him only a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is on display in the El Fotómata Gallery in de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16. October.
