"Car bee" prevents precipitation
This time, Nissan was inspired by advances in the development of accident-protecting technologies in nature, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the pattern of flying bees, thus preventing collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. robot have developed, in collaboration with the Centre for Advancement in Scientific and Technology Research, Japan’s prestigious University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doi, CEO of public relations for technology, research and brand development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four safety shield zones.
The robot is tasked with strengthening the ability to prevent collisions in this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in their personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual function, engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to two meters in the 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"At the moment an obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive manoeuvres are absolutely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction in which it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and behave according to this data.
It does not require the storage of information or logical intuition from previous manoeuvres, thanks to which it can operate without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we're not talking about a gig or a mega."
This is the first step in the development of new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts for use in production cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the finish line while avoiding obstacles on the way.
Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will need to install "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol has to install a system in his car that prevents him from starting a car while drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Prosecutor General’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its aim is to return the driver to the wheel, therefore drivers will also have to take a traffic re-education course.
In addition to the National Transport Safety Authority, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Car Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of the carmakers charged more than once while driving drunk in this state will get behind the wheel again.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if a higher than the permitted concentration of alcohol is recorded.
Its price exceeds 1 000 euros and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study conducted in this sense in the U.S. in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device decreased by 65% during the first year since its introduction.
In Spain, 115 people could save their lives each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help its introduction, because the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, but the necessary regulation of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The equipment is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been rehearsally installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Members will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party), in which it is recommended to install this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
