Talking in sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may startle you, but it's actually insignificant.
It is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilokvie.
It is quite common, especially for children and adolescents.
I'm sure they told many of you that he was talking in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime in high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is not just one reason to explain her rise.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night terrors, enuresis nocturna (night bedwetting) or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or inflamed situations.
In any case, it is a little-explored phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (cries, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great strength, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that provokes great anxiety and manifests himself in this way.
We have said that this is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind some very simple preventive measures, such as:
Trying not to upset the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who can relax the work, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them to gain a certain inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somnilokvia appears, try to keep calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that from what happened, the next day he will not remember anything.
Useful advice
Don't be him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if you seem to be suffering very much several times in a row, it would be advisable to turn to advice or find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
