Interview - Blood, which is again certain
Hema-Québec yesterday celebrated the 10th anniversary of the founding and its president, dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced, having become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the trust of the public, which was seriously shaken after the scandal with contaminated blood in the 80's and 90's.
As is common knowledge, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Due to this drama and the wave of public displeasure, the Canadian government began a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting the report, some provinces set in motion a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was held by Gélinea's committee.
After Gélineau's and Krever's report, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started his activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary.
"The situation was daunting.
With a continuous effort to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this field over the years to come, we have regained public confidence," he says, proudly adding that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the Quebec population trusted Héma-Québek.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, in Europe, we witnessed the occurrence of many cases of human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman, who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread through blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, if we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take excluding measures.
In April 1999, we therefore turned down blood from people who had been staying in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that sticking to the principle of prudence made sense.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect HIV: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which tests were previously used.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing about it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
One in 12 million people in the world today is exposed to the risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV.
"In other words, it means that before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Because Héma-Québec distributes 400 000 to 500 000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission to be discovered through a blood product.
I believe that today we can completely calmly get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for recovery," says the head of the leadership of Hém-Québek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what disease element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues dr. Décaryová and stresses that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also take into account sufficient supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment for cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has implications for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecians permitted to donation.”
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, corresponding to the admissibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not admitted on average because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and whether they have visited a country where mud fever is rampant are excluded for a year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, members of the network of donors need to be supplemented in proportion to how they get older and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to give blood, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and freezed before they are stored at Héma-Québek, which also manages the only public bank of blood from the cord of Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, abounds in stem-rich blood, which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth blood sample from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we assume that we will take over a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
