During his speech, pictures were projected behind his back in a kind of picture grinder.
On three giant canvases ran a loop with remarkable images of hydroelectric dams, downs, Quebec from the perspective of "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Generous means, similar to the pre-election period.
At a press conference, the prime minister refused to rule out calling an early election in the autumn, although he pointed out that he had a very busy schedule.
The "Plan North" forms the fourth dimension of the "vision" that the Prime Minister intends for Quebec, a vision of a "new economic space" that includes an agreement with France on labor, a convention between Canada and Europe, and agreements with Ontario.
Despite the fact that the opening of the North - northern territory on the 49th parallel - the prime minister has often mentioned in his statements recently, it has never been the subject of a presentation before.
However, the Prime Minister limited himself to explaining why the North represents a "juvenile with enormous potential," but did not give a deadline, investment amount, or a clear priority in future projects.
At the most, he mentioned several approaches to the points that could be further developed: in particular hydropower plants, forests, but in particular the mining sector, encouraged by the growth of rapidly developing countries and the restoration of public infrastructures.
The North, according to Charest's list, contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds."
This "territory twice the size of France is in our country", "it is in Quebec.
And he's not just with us, but he's in us," he pointed out, as if to show that he's appealing to a certain national founding myth.
Québec was built to a large extent in relation to the North, the Prime Minister highlighted: the hunt for gold in Abitibi, Quebec Engineering, James's Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future," he added after pausing theatrically to view the huge map behind his back.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a part of Labrador that Quebec has always demanded, the Prime Minister specified during a press conference.
"This is a traditional position that has been repeated by all governments so far.
There is one border line on which there has been no convention for a long time, and if a suitable opportunity arises, in the name of the government I will take that position again.”
Otherwise, “it is also necessary to rethink our vision of the North in the context of climate change,” he said, referring to the north-west crossing, which will open year-round as a result of the melting of glaciers.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that taking up territory is becoming a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the territory, the indigenous peoples and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would be beneficial to them, especially the young.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (a former Pequist MP from Ungavy), have already begun negotiations with about thirty communities.
The work was started by the Inter-Ministerial Committee, chaired by Benoît Pelliter, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important position.
The prime minister does not rule out a major meeting, "not necessarily a summit," but a moment when "a common vision will be set out."
Moreover, the development of the North should be in line with the principles of sustainable development.
The North plan will be "commonly designed, structured and environmentally friendly," he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as a fluently follow-up to the vision of the liberal prime ministers who preceded it.
"Like the liberals who preceded us, we have changed our mindset to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development."
This was, after all, one of the still-shoveling themes of the weekend, which was launched on Friday with a big cocktail highlighting the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's rise to the party's lead.
One of the adopted resolutions proposes to re-christen the Beauharnois headquarters at the Adélard-Godbout Dam.
"From Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, through Lesage, who carried out the Peaceful Revolution and the nationalization of hydropower, to Bourass, who created James's bay, our party was able to shape the future," said Jean Charest.
At a press conference, he appealed to another authority, this time a conservative one, on John Diefenbaker's "Roads to the North" program, the prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
When it came to the Eastmain1a-Ruper dam hydroelectric power plant, Charest stressed that its launch was planned for 2012.
"I only say it between us, but I plan to be there," he confided to his member base, raising considerable applause.
The same prime minister who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008, and undoubtedly not in 2009, he did not rule out the possibility of calling an election in the autumn of this year, which is allowed by law.
However, he stressed that his program is packed, especially by the Federal Council's mission in China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend congress provided the Liberals' chief with a platform for some nationalist resolutions, especially some "efforts to amend the constitution" that have passed very smoothly: the PLQ (the Liberal Party of Quebec) requires particularly recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
It also wishes Québec to appoint a part of the members of the Canadian Council for Radio and Television Broadcasting who would have veto power in the event of decisions taken in Quebec.
From the opposition side, Plan North was accepted skeptically in its main features.
PQ (Parti Québecois) chief Pauline Marois once again pulled out the Northern Quebec Development Policy, which Landry's government launched in 2001.
According to her, when the government of the Liberals came to power in 2003, it renounced the fulfillment of this policy.
If she could stick to it, "we'd be further along today," Marois remarked alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (where the election is taking place today) of Françoise Mercure.
ADQ said it would support the adoption of the North Plan in government.
"However, we wish it wasn't just theatre," explained Sébastien Proulx, a leader representing Maria Dumonta, who is returning from the holidays today.
