Opinions - Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter to Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched the prosecution of three authors and a poor little publishing house for insult to honour in order to spark a "transparent public debate" and is demanding six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honour, but by law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver completely ignores this fundamental distinction.
Or is it perhaps the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate to bring to a bad anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced fight with an army of attorneys backed by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
Moreover, the tactics in these unbalanced struggles often consist in the ruination of the defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings, which will be clogged by the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, scare anyone who would dare to pursue this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the matter to the public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas, and not in the wounds of the baton.
Therefore, mine companies were not enough to open their books, their documentation and establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion and has rejected petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate," while also despising the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president's world refers only to boldly paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrowed conception of this term.
In a democracy, even servers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public that supports authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and assess the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in the context of what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant’s mouth is to be shut (in the context of his prosecution of the “public debate” Barrick, by the way, has just filed an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them that they should stop using this term...).
Apart from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of research and the search for truth that are essential to every democratic society.
Overall, he denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that do not appeal to the rich companies of this world without putting ourselves on the face of repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do this?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed it if it had followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to a response.
The university environment to which we belong has always been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's over-lawsuit clearly shows that despite what it claims, it has no appetite to have a transparent debate.
It's a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it's time for governments to put in place measures that would limit such a type of wrongful prosecution.
Operations to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest rescue economic plan since the Greater Crisis of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use 700 billion U.S. dollars to slow the financial crisis that has been looming Wall Street for months must still be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring the repayment of deposited public money, new measures to capture the amount of houses seized due to default, and also the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to executives of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican official at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress and come to an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a Bush administration official.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis just occurring on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"That's a crucial point: if we don't do it, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption of the everyday life of Americans will be huge," Republican Judd Gregg said.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have run to the maximum of fear of the effect of further failures on investors' mood.
The designated time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates for U.S. president were invited to negotiate later, and both expressed their way more for the deal, but without omitting to express their displeasure with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added some measures, particularly to allow owners to maintain their residence, and wage measures for heads of state-saved firms.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the waves of television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I've read [show] that this is something we'll all have to digest and through which we can move forward.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the 700-billion-dollar plan is to buy back, with taxpayers' money, questionable claims and risky and unsaleable assets of U.S. financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and disintegration of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of last week's first draft agreement was due to Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats agreed that for some of the "toxic" assets of companies having difficulties, the government will only guarantee but not buy them, there is a belief that the impasse is over.
In an effort to bring conflicting views in Congress, a measure has been attached setting out that the government will be able to introduce new fees that would help it get its deposit back if, as a result, the program would have to take over losses for five years.
The new plan foresees a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion will be added, if the president deems it necessary.
A deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends in case of profit and which he will be able to sell again when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of real estate associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of the award and compensation paid to executives of the affected firms.
The architects of the plan would like to submit a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, voices were still rising against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's perfectly obvious that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House of Commons Finance Committee, said in an address to voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, earning money from taxpayers is not the answer.”
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, a congressman's host nicknamed "the Sceptic Committee", presents the matter differently, but there is the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed professors of economics, among them three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us: we are asking Congress not to rush too much and to examine carefully which path to take," he said.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a global crisis.
After the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced a partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion USD).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its rival, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion USD) as a result of the crisis of risky loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, among Europe's twenty largest banks and among the top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And it is precisely the savers and households that can appreciate in these uncertain times.”
On the other side of the English Channel, it seems so far, the British government has begun nationalising another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was supposed to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to his announcement yesterday, the branches and accounts of the clients of the British bank will be bought by the Spanish bank Santander.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government must nationalise since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - The Death of a Socially Engaged Icon
His beauty with azure's eyes had long represented his trump card, according to others, a weakness.
Has this American actor taken away with a charming smile out of narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and unfailing talent that were inherent in him also distanced him from the power category that breeds true stars.
What a long runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at 83 at his Connecticut ranch as a result of lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less magnificent than Brando, to whom he was similar and for a long time his rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly a more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often breeds beautiful babies.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and a mother of Hungarian origin.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
No exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in it, the whole country in love with self-made man, a warrior in the war in the Pacific, wounded in a battle that in the early 1950s studied acting in Yale, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumphs in the theater, television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a car racer who ranked second in the 24-hour race at Le Mans in 1979, and also a sexual symbol, despite having formed a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With it also leave the downsides of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of their own show-business, which will forever remain mysterious to some extent.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend caused dizziness to film lovers, while his big roles rival each other on the black screen of memories.
After him, he defiles more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams, is re-emerging in memory.
From a less distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by marriages that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans went down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, a tortured, violent, memorable delinquent from Somebody Up There Likes Me, Robert Wis, a role for James Dean, taken over after his death, which made Newman a real acquaintance in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, the 1973 Academy Award for Best Picture.
The bitter and vengeful pool player in the amazing Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961) will play the same character in Martin Scorsese's Color of Money, bringing him the only Oscar in seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, it was him.
And again, him.
In his professional career, various epochs compete with each other.
The youngsters know him mainly thanks to the iconic Slap Shot George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, a non-traditional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy Brothers Coen.
He then completed his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike several film legends that left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the business for a long time, though he condemned Hollywood with its tinkles, pomp and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humor, "a lively challenge to underplaying," judging that in his performances he pushed too hard.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as if on a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played the first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, scoundrels and desperate people whose declines and rebellions reflected in his perfect features.
As director Newman has revealed little-known pages of his shy sensitivity.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (according to the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence) in which his wife, Joanne Woodward, played the lead role, gives a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
He dedicated his son, Scott, to his son, whom he lost due to an overdose, in 1984, the film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness.
In a surge of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (they played together in The Sting and in Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared: "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generousness, love of life, such are the main qualities of the deceased actor.
Apart from his legendary career, a great civil rights campaigner, ecology, independent film, opponent of the decline of Hollywood also leaves.
We were used to seeing his portrait on vials of wine vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, which might have seemed rather tacky to us, although it was a gag at first.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for a difficult childhood.
Newman, rather than being lulled by glory, engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing these sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a bright and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory Zuschlag & spol.?
Soon, 8. October, the trial will begin in criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
In addition to other crimes, including the forgery of documents, the politician and his associates are charged with long-term and systematic criminal fraud, resulting in extremely significant damage.
According to prosecutors, they used money raised in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and self-government - in total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, in part to the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also reported by the investigating authority, consisted in the fact that the money raised in public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no actual consideration and never lived up to the obligations made by the associations.
According to the indictment, a large portion of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Yoga-Fváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The name of which companies the production of invoices was to take place was decided, among other things, on a circular road along the northern shore of Balaton, to which he sent István Lados János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, the first one was supposed to look out for guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he applied for bills for his consumption, according to which invoices submitted in public tenders were then produced, among other things, by the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, respectively the Municipality of the Capital.
Invoices were mostly issued by István Lados with his companion András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip," Lados picked out a beer hall.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, this hospitality catering facility provided for the ninety-member group of the Biztos Pont association.
However, according to the company’s manager, not so many people would suddenly fit into this facility.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later Együtt and Harmadik Éveredért was teeming with formal and content errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
However, the fillers of the forms with a rich imagination overdid it even when they put on the documents a company also dedicated to the hospitality industry - Pigal s. r. o., in whose account, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor's office, the documents sounding in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even figure.
The head of the company Győző Farkas told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and he was shown invoices, he immediately knew that it was fake documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were on the stamp in the wrong place."
As he added, apart from the formalities, he did not agree that according to the invoice, they accommodated a hundred people, because they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, food was also mentioned on the invoice, while their restaurant has not been working for a long time.
Zealous invoice manufacturers have not convinced themselves that the Budapest travel agency organizes only foreign trips and on an invoice with payment in cash, which also did not coincide with the company's billing practice, they said foolishly as a service of mediating a trip to Hungary.
Moreover, as the investigation showed, VAT was also stated in the document, although the organisation of travel to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
The four documents issued by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. disagreed, among other things, on the amount of VAT. The company’s activities are not covered by the 25 percent, but by the 15 percent VAT, in addition to which the hotel staff issued only printed invoices, but the invoice produced was written by hand.
In addition, the "publishers" spoiled the invoice, for example, by stating to one company how it became clear thanks to the investigation of the prosecutor's office, as an activity carried out by road transport of goods, which the company originally did not perform on investment advice.
That the invoices are issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Éveredért and the XXI associations. The backing of Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont was false, in addition, also because of formal deviations - an inadequate invoice format and a false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they issued the invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not notice that HIB s. r. o. z Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time of 2001, when the group from the Fiatal Városért association was eating, precisely why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
Invoices were exposed consciously
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation issued accounts for about four million forints for the Harmadik Éveredért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták organization.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s. r. o. was forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused Ludovice Györfi.
Biogate s. r. o. also cooperated with Zuschlag and his associates, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and Atlasz and Vörösfenyő with invoices worth about five million forints, for which there was no actual economic activity.
Nor the movement of money, because the invoices created were later cancelled, which, of course, the organizations had already forgotten to state in their documents.
Another group of invoicing companies includes those who had ties to the defendants.
Thus, for example, Iván Kubatov was the authorized representative of the Ukrainian executive of Delta Trió s. r. o., engaged in the trading of fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, on which, however, the company is not to be found.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment funds worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the data found by the investigation, the Kiskunhala company Cash Investment s. r. o., which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, purchased these invoices.
The managing director of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was supposed to hand over documents concerning the company in 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the associations Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt and Harmadik Éveredért on behalf of the company and himself accepted their consideration.
At the request of Ivan Kubatov, the Romanian bricklayers were founded by Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s. r. o. and Jos-Investment k. s.
In fact, neither of the companies worked, according to the defendant because they did not get a job.
Nevertheless, the companies were of his advantage, because at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, who also prepared their instruments of incorporation, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations connected to Zuschlag.
On behalf of the companies Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave organizations a total of 15 invoices worth 14.2 million forints.
The prosecutor's office concluded that Kubatov came to 10 percent of the amounts listed on invoices and VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri k. t. to issue fictional invoices, this time for the tender for the Biztos Pont association.
In January 2006, the associations Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals for the public tender of the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organization of the Socialist Party.
They received 500 thousand forints, but did not spend the amounts on the targets set out in the proposals.
In order to make this not clear, TMA submitted five fictional invoices from Works Team s. r. o.
These invoices were found during a search of the house in the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, a portion of the defendants are likely to describe the course of the production of invoices, as they have already done in the prosecution.
It may be more interesting if the main defendant János Zuschlag decides to reveal everything himself.
His statement so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to interpret everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for the payment of a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, perhaps the Socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it upon himself.
He may have been offended, after all, because his requests to ease the conditions of his detention, namely his placement under house arrest, have remained unheard so far.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes, who have done much more damage that have not yet been paid, are free to walk or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
Psychology of Trumping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this familiar - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to fall behind in the eBay auction type competition, so they prefer to pay even too high a price.
Using an experimental auction, the research attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in the actuated auction, using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to examine the active areas of the brain of the experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but when playing the auction, the important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively during the loss.
This brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system in addition to many other functions.
According to researchers, the price can therefore be explained by trying to avoid a sharp reaction of the striate.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the economists carried out a financial cross-cutting survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were licensed against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive another 15 dollars for the reward.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, but in case of losing, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, of everything in the fact that one was emphasized by the win and the other by losing.
However, members of the group playing "against the loss" were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they had explained phenomena observable at auctions of the joys of victory and avoidance of risk.
It wasn’t until neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories so that we had now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York’s Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms contain many similarities, symptomatic is inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the cause of the disease, spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E to the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, travelers should protect themselves by vaccination against the A and B virus, there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of the infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, the urge to vomit.
Then, jaundice is formed on the skin and whites of the eye, the stools are lightened and the urine darkens. Treatment can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten people infected is treated medically.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of those infected do not even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms occur in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, regular depistage, is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the projected global number of individuals infected with the Chronic Hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove already routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing contagiousness and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
