Smart car imitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has constructed a BIO23C biomimetic robotic control system, a robotic minicar equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which actually closely resembles our safety protective packaging," Kazuhiro Doi, brand general manager for technology PR and research and development, explained at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the folded eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C in the 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into a collision prevention operation.
The obstacle is captured in a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to imitate the bee's movements and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this puncture manoeuvre takes place in an absolutely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety protective packaging, inside which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, in the case of a robotic car, only the possibility of rotating motion, acceleration and deceleration was applied.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the ability to process, much less data storage.
This mechanism must be processed and responded to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store them and respond using the intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so he constantly uses only memory of the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology to immediately avoid, which Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding the path of the lying obstacles, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
