President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, after which reports of the deal were also welcomed to the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made at night and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
Moreover, the program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal, which was supposed to be about spending a total of 700 billion dollars on the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of £700 billion in the first round, by using 250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to decide the matter on Monday, and the Treasury will buy mortgage-backed securities for them, which are rated poor quality, and the fate of the remaining 100 billion dollars will depend on the president’s decision.
The program will be controlled by a special corps, of which the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
Spending the second half of 700 billion dollars will depend on the next congressional decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply combined tactics within the meaning of the Act: it can simultaneously buy back low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase can also take place directly within the auctions, the ministry's competent officials said.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance will guarantee them a guarantee for funds representing a reason for concern, for which companies will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend up to 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system, whether it will be a large-scale purchase of the wrong funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major money institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
Bank chiefs, who have run into trouble and are waiting to help the state, can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which is simply called "golden parachute" in overseas slang.
