Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 due to the previous month, compared to August 2007 by 12.9 percent, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in the industry were up 1.1 percent compared with July 2008, down 3.9 percent year-on-year.
Production prices in the industry were higher by 0.7 percent as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, rising by 3.2 percent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose only minimally, by 0.1 percent, given the previous month.
Also, domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industries increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The biggest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to a month-on-month increase in prices in the production of bag and saddlery products by 4.6 percent and footwear production by 2.5 percent, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical and product production sector (1.6 percent).
The price reduction occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), the production of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors, which have a lot of weight in domestic sales of industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the ongoing effect of the officially determined increase in gas prices running from 1. July.
