Fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people's data on drug purchases, often dismiss the possibility of entering into an insurance contract with a bidder.
Data protection experts fear the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme that binds the use of drug prescription data in any case to the person's permission.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to the fox," Richard Dick, author of the drug prescribing program, said in a statement.
Insurance companies make premiums and amounts paid in the event of insurance claims dependent on the health status of the interested parties, and if the risk is assessed as too large, they will not even take out insurance with it.
They had previously sent the person concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick devised a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer easily finds out from the pharmacies what medications the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself will infer what disease he suffers from and what his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys a large number of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it refers to the fact that he has virtually uncontrollably high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in the category with a higher risk.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so the insurance company has almost no work left except for paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that many drugs can also be used for several purposes, some compounds are, for example, usable against migraine or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-enhancing factor, while the first mentioned difficulties do not.
In order to request and process data, special companies have been created who, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, will ask the patient for permission.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not punished them for their negligence so far.
Some companies have recently been processing the results of laboratory examinations that associate with the data about the medications used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health condition of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, at the same time the control of their use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to control even businesses specializing in providing data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: therefore, he developed his programme in such a way that the assignment of the data is tied to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that the consent in question can hardly be denied, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are, after all, somewhat dependent on the fox goodwill.
